<whpage pageid="pgComponents" desc="WebHub Components for Delphi">
<whpagesettings inherit="a">
downLink=DEMOS:OVERVIEW
</whpagesettings>
(~drShowcaseGlobalHeader~)
This application was written to show all the non-Delphi features of
WebHub -- that is, those that people can implement using regular HTML
plus WebHub macros.
<p>
If you are a programmer, you can take this much further.  The overall
architecture is extremely open since you can customize event handlers
for all the Delphi components as well as create your own <i>web action</i>
components.  Non-Delphi programmers can add features by writing .DLLs.
<b>WebHub covers the basics for you, leaving you free to focus on the
more creative aspects of web site development.</b>
<p>
Please refer to the WebHub User Manual to pursue these topics
further.  To try demos that do involve custom Delphi code and
database features, visit the Demos page linked on the left.  Full Delphi source is available for all demo projects.
(~drShowcaseGlobalFooter~)
</whpage>

<whdroplet name="ulPgComponents">
(~JUMP|DEMOS:OVERVIEW|Demos~)
</whdroplet>

<whpage pageid="pgDBComponents" desc="Database components">
<whpagesettings inherit="a">
</whpagesettings>
(~drShowcaseGlobalHeader~)
Most sophisticated web sites use an underlying database.
WebHub includes a set of components to make database publishing
easy.  These can be used by a Delphi programmer to run queries
against Oracle, Sybase, Informix, Interbase, Paradox, dBase,
and Access tables.  (You can connect to <i>any</i> database
supported by Delphi.)  Data entry is also supported.
(~drShowcaseGlobalFooter~)
</whpage>

</whteko>
